{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":8912,"record_hash":"sha256:b9a59fde24ed2273a7c428a61261bc1ef0991133e5862c661ff862f5aa0bcf87","timestamp":"2026-05-07T20:19:01.304Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"::code-comment{title=\\\"[P1] Session IDs bypass redaction via GitMeta keys/scalars\\\" body=\\\"`TranscriptEnvelope` redacts copied `session_id`, but the same value is still persisted as the GitMeta key segment and as the `session-id` scalar. Since redaction treats UUID-shaped IDs as sensitive, a UUID/high-entropy session can be hidden inside the envelope while still exposed in metadata names/values. POC-sized fix: hash all session IDs for `session_key`, and redact or drop the scalar.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs\\\" start=258 end=260 priority=1 confidence=0.92}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] Absolute local paths are stored despite being validation-only\\\" body=\\\"`cwd` and canonical `source-path` are persisted raw. That leaks usernames and local transcript layout now that capture always writes, and it conflicts with the capture-layer comment that transcript CWDs are only used to validate repository membership. POC-sized fix: omit these fields, store repo-relative CWD only, or store a path hash where identity is useful.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs\\\" start=261 end=267 priority=2 confidence=0.86}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] Obvious short secrets are not redacted\\\" body=\\\"Object values are redacted only by token length/entropy, without considering generic secret-bearing keys. That misses common low-entropy or human-chosen values such as `password`, `passphrase`, or short bearer tokens, while still storing full transcript records. A tiny exact-key denylist would close this without becoming a scanner framework.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=40 end=49 priority=2 confidence=0.78}\\n\\nEquilibrium is close, but not quite reached. The main remaining imbalance is that envelope redaction is careful, while GitMeta key/scalar storage still preserves the same sensitive identifiers and local paths in easier-to-discover places.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T20:19:01.304Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"::code-comment{title=\\\"[P1] Session IDs bypass redaction via GitMeta keys/scalars\\\" body=\\\"`TranscriptEnvelope` redacts copied `session_id`, but the same value is still persisted as the GitMeta key segment and as the `session-id` scalar. Since redaction treats UUID-shaped IDs as sensitive, a UUID/high-entropy session can be hidden inside the envelope while still exposed in metadata names/values. POC-sized fix: hash all session IDs for `session_key`, and redact or drop the scalar.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs\\\" start=258 end=260 priority=1 confidence=0.92}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] Absolute local paths are stored despite being validation-only\\\" body=\\\"`cwd` and canonical `source-path` are persisted raw. That leaks usernames and local transcript layout now that capture always writes, and it conflicts with the capture-layer comment that transcript CWDs are only used to validate repository membership. POC-sized fix: omit these fields, store repo-relative CWD only, or store a path hash where identity is useful.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs\\\" start=261 end=267 priority=2 confidence=0.86}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] Obvious short secrets are not redacted\\\" body=\\\"Object values are redacted only by token length/entropy, without considering generic secret-bearing keys. That misses common low-entropy or human-chosen values such as `password`, `passphrase`, or short bearer tokens, while still storing full transcript records. A tiny exact-key denylist would close this without becoming a scanner framework.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=40 end=49 priority=2 confidence=0.78}\\n\\nEquilibrium is close, but not quite reached. The main remaining imbalance is that envelope redaction is careful, while GitMeta key/scalar storage still preserves the same sensitive identifiers and local paths in easier-to-discover places.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>"}]}}}